SIMPLE: host
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Host
<hw>Host</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>hostia</ets> sacrifice, victim, from <ets>hostire</ets> to
strike.]</ety> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>The consecrated wafer,
believed to be the body of Christ, which in the Mass is offered as a
sacrifice; also, the bread before consecration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the Latin Vulgate the word was applied to the Savior
as being an offering for the sins of men.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Host</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Host
<hw>Host</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>host</ets>, <ets>ost</ets>, OF. <ets>host</ets>, <ets>ost</ets>,
fr. L. <ets>hostis</ets> enemy, LL., army. See <er>Guest</er>, and cf.
<er>Host</er> a landlord.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An army; a number of
men gathered for war.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>host</qex> so great as covered all the field.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any great number or multitude; a throng.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And suddenly there was with the angel a multitude of the heavenly
<qex>host</qex> praising God.</q> <rj><qau>Luke ii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All at once I saw a crowd,⟦br⟧
A <qex>host</qex>, of golden daffodils.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Host</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Host
<hw>Host</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>host</ets>, <ets>ost</ets>, OF. <ets>hoste</ets>, <ets>oste</ets>,
F. <ets>h⟦ocir⟧te</ets>, from L. <ets>hospes</ets> a stranger who is
treated as a guest, he who treats another as his guest, a hostl prob.
fr. <ets>hostis</ets> stranger, enemy (akin to E. <ets>guest</ets> a
visitor) + <ets>potis</ets> able; akin to Skr. <ets>pati</ets> master,
lord. See <er>Host</er> an army, <er>Possible</er>, and cf.
<er>Hospitable</er>, <er>Hotel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who
receives or entertains another, whether gratuitously or for
compensation; one from whom another receives food, lodging, or
entertainment; a landlord.</def> <au>Chaucer.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Fair
<xex>host</xex> and Earl.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Tennyson.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Time is like a fashionable <qex>host</qex>,⟦br⟧
That slightly shakes his parting guest by the hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Any animal or plant affording
lodgment or subsistence to a parasitic or commensal organism. <as>Thus a
tree is a <ex>host</ex> of an air plant growing upon it</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Host</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Host
<hw>Host</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give entertainment to.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Host</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Host
<hw>Host</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To lodge at an inn; to take up
entertainment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Where you shall
<xex>host</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hosta</ent>⟦br⟧
